### Using useSuspenseQuery with React Suspense and ErrorBoundary

Source: https://github.com/powersync-ja/powersync-js/blob/main/packages/react/README.md

Demonstrates integrating `useSuspenseQuery` with React's built-in Suspense and ErrorBoundary components. The hook suspends while data is loading, causing the `<Suspense fallback>` to render. Errors during data fetching are caught by the `<ErrorBoundary fallback>`. The actual data fetching component is wrapped inside Suspense and ErrorBoundary. Requires `@powersync/react`, `react`, and `react-error-boundary`.

```JSX
// TodoListDisplaySuspense.jsx
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';
import { Suspense } from 'react';
import { useSuspenseQuery } from '@powersync/react';

const TodoListContent = () => {
  const { data: todoLists } = useSuspenseQuery("SELECT * FROM lists");

  return (
    <ul>
      {todoLists.map((list) => (
        <li key={list.id}>{list.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
};


export const TodoListDisplaySuspense = () => {
  return (
  <ErrorBoundary fallback={<div>Something went wrong</div>}>
    <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading todo lists...</div>}>
      <TodoListContent />
    </Suspense>
  </ErrorBoundary>
  );
};
```

